BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Retour d'XP et perspectives sur le développement de projets Open 
 Source
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Paris:20170921T190000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Paris:20170921T210000
UID:https://www.meetup.com/software-craftsmanship-bdx/events/240001683/@co
 mmunity-events
DESCRIPTION:🔗 https://www.meetup.com/software-craftsmanship-bdx/events/
 240001683/\n📍 le node\, 12 rue des Faussets\, Bordeaux\, France\n\nDeux
  figures majeures de la communauté Open Source .Net/F# viennent nous parl
 er de leur chemin dans l'eco-système Open Source\, de leur retour d'expé
 rience et des perspectives futures.\nCes talks seront en anglais\, et ont 
 une portée plus large que le monde .Net\, même si c'est cet eco-système
  qui sera utilisé comme exemple.\nLe premier talk de la soirée sera :\nP
 ath to happiness with Open Source\, par Krzysztof Cieslak\nOpen Source So
 ftware has already changed the world\, it powers our phones\, computers\, 
 Internet. Even big\, conservative companies\, that couple of years ago sta
 ted that OSS is dangerous\, nowadays are building their products in the op
 en\, and are trying to more deeply cooperate with communities using those 
 products.  In this talk I’ll try to show why investing into Open Source
  is really good\, pragmatic way of building a software. I’ll describe th
 e problem from 3 different point of views – company building its project
 s in the open\, company using OSS to build its projects and single develop
 er that wants to participate in this global OSS movement – and I’ll tr
 y to show what advantages can OSS bring in those cases.\nBio: \nChris is 
 software developer\, consultant\, founder of Lambda Factory (http://lambda
 factory.io). He's author of Ionide (http://ionide.io/)\, Forge (http://for
 ge.run)\, Fornax (https://gitlab.com/Krzysztof-Cieslak/Fornax)\, project o
 wner and maintainer of VSCode-Elm(https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/ite
 ms?itemName=sbrink.elm) and contributor to many OSS projects. Chris is als
 o international speaker\, that tries to convince developers around the wor
 ld that OSS and FP are good\, pragmatic choices for writing software. You 
 can find him on Twitter as @k_cieslak\, GitHub - @Krzysztof-Cieslak and r
 ead his blog.\nEt le second :\nSurviving OSS success\, par Alfonso Garcia
 -Caro\nThere it is\, finally\, your OSS project is ready for a release. Yo
 u’ve put a lot of time\, effort and love in it and now you see with sati
 sfaction the “Build Pass” green tick. You write a tweet to announce it
  to the world and then the worst thing that can happen happens: Success! P
 eople start using the project\, Github notifications never stop\, you get 
 invited to talk about it at conferences... but like Uncle Ben used to say:
  “With great power comes great responsibility”. Suddenly the project b
 ecomes a big part of your life\, people start using it in production and y
 ou discover you’ve to learn how do HR\, PR\, IT Support and may other ac
 ronyms you didn’t know about to deal everyday with competitors\, contrib
 utors and users sometimes enthusiastic and sometimes demanding.\nAlfonso G
 arcía-Caro\, author of Fable (an F# to JS compiler)\, has tasted a bit th
 is kind of success. One day before FableConf the first conference dedicate
 d to his project (he still wonders how this happened)\, Alfonso will expla
 in how he managed to elude a sanity break (so far). Obviously he won’t h
 ave time to prepare any slide\, so the talk will mostly be incoherent ramb
 ling. Come to watch a show of bad English with some broken French\, and ce
 rtify Alfonso has zero improvisation skills!\n\nCommunauté: okiwi
LOCATION:le node\, 12 rue des Faussets\, Bordeaux\, France
TZID:Europe/Paris
URL:https://www.meetup.com/software-craftsmanship-bdx/events/240001683/
END:VEVENT
